## v1.1.0 (2026-05-07)

**Changed by:** ProjectScylla #1887 split into PRs #1932 and #1933 (JSON-logging/tracing/metrics remediation)
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- Added new section "Splitting a Single Issue into Parallel Sub-Tasks" (Phase 0) covering the
  one-issue → N-sub-tasks pattern with explicit hot-file ownership, append-only docs rules,
  and merge-method detection
- Added 4 new Failed Attempts rows: pixi env-name assumption, default `--rebase` merge flag,
  shared docs end-of-file collision invalidating "still TODO" lists, missed pre-commit on
  conflict-resolved files
- Added merge-method detection step (`gh repo view --json ...MergeAllowed`) to Quick Reference
- Added `pre-commit run --files <changed>` after rebase conflict resolution as mandatory step
- Bumped version to 1.1.0 (minor: new pattern + new failures, no breaking changes)
- Upgraded `verification` from `unverified` to `verified-ci` based on the merged PRs

### Why

Original skill (v1.0.0) covered N independent issues in parallel waves. The salient distinction
captured here — splitting ONE multi-part issue into N truly independent sub-tasks — has different
coordination characteristics: shared docs files, shared config files (`pyproject.toml`,
`cli/main.py`), and the need to detect "still TODO" lists that one sub-task's work obsoletes for
the other. Foundation issue #1887 in ProjectScylla produced a clean test case: PR #1932 squash-merged
green; PR #1933 hit a markdownlint conflict on `docs/dev/tracing.md` from end-of-file appends,
resolved with one rebase + one fix-up commit.

